      <div xml:id="NA171-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu pirivuṇarttappaṭṭa tōḻi talaimakaṭku uraittatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante to whom the separation had been announced said to HER.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA171">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            nīrnacaik kūkkiya vuyaval yāṉai</l>
<l>            vēṉiṟ kuṉṟattu vevvaraik kavāa</l>
<l>            ṉilañcelac cellāk kayantalaik kuḻavi</l>
<l>            cēriyam peṇṭir neñcat teṟiya</l>
<l>            vūrāṉ kaṉṟoṭu pukutu nāṭaṉ </l>
<l>            paṉmalai yaruñcura miṟappi ṉamviṭ</l>
<l>            ṭiyāṅku vallunar maṟṟē ñāṅkar</l>
<l>            viṉaippūṇ ṭeṇmaṇi vīḻa niṟappak</l>
<l>            kaḻutukāl koḷḷum poḻutukoḷ pāṉā</l>
<l>            ḷārva neñcamō ṭaḷaii </l>
<l>            mārpuṟap paṭuttaṉ marīiya kaṇṇē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>If he traverses the difficult desert with many mountains, deserting us,</l>
<l rend="indent">the man from a land, where the soft-headed [elephant] calf, un[able to] go</l>
<l rend="indent2">when the suffering [mother] elephant, shaken by yearning for water, goes</l>
<l rend="indent2">from the ground to the slopes of hot mountains in the hills(?)<note place="foot">What is to be conveyed by this triple row of words for mountain: <term xml:lang="ta">kuṉram - varai - kavāam</term>?</note> in summer,</l>
<l rend="indent">enters the village with the calfs of the cows,</l>
<l rend="indent3">so that it strikes the hearts of the women in the quarter,</l>
<l>– how will [my] eyes be strong<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vallunar/valluna</term>: the variant in -<term xml:lang="ta">ar</term> is attractive, giving a high-class verb to the eyes, thereby attributing even stronger the notion of the eyes’ life of their own, their being uncontrollable.</note> [enough] henceforth</l>
<l rend="indent3">that joined together in sleeping(?)<note place="foot">How is <term xml:lang="ta">paṭuttal</term> supposed to give the meaning sleeping? On the other hand, the context is clear, and the paṭutal of ET certainly is the lectio facilior.</note> when they had [his] chest,</l>
<l rend="indent3">mingling with affectionate hearts</l>
<l rend="indent3">at midnight, taken as the period when demons take [their] time(?),<note place="foot">What is the notion connected with <term xml:lang="ta">kāl koḷḷum</term>? Is this simply the hour of spirits?</note></l>
<l>while [now] they change colour when clear sapphires</l>
<l rend="indent4">[as if] from crafted ornaments descend [from them](?)<note place="foot">This line poses problems indeed. The second half has as many variants as there are texts. My suggestion is to stick to the reading given in G1+2 and take it as a simile for the eyes that are crying now HER nights are no longer spent with HIM. T.V.G. reads (as usual) with EN: <term xml:lang="ta">vīḻtaṉa nikarppa</term>, and he takes it with the commentary as an elliptical simile for the eyes, namely spears adorned with bells that are sent off. He cannot name a parallel for such a notion. Dakshinamurthy 2001 also inserts the spears but connects them with the movement of the demons.</note>?</l>
        </lg>
